    "created_at": "2022-12-05T11:54:21Z",
    "updated_at": "2022-12-05T11:54:21Z",
    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "The relevant cases are:\r\n\r\n### Show always \"Request to join\"\r\n\r\n1) If the community has manual approval, works fine\r\n2) If the community has auto approval, but the owner is offline/busy, it's consistent\r\n3) If the community has auto approval, and the owner is online, joining will be quick in theory, so that won't be an issue\r\n\r\n### Show always \"join\"\r\n\r\n1) If the community has manual approval, the user might be a bit surprised that it has to wait\r\n2) If the community has auto approval, but the owner is offline/busy, same as above\r\n3) If the community has auto approval, and the owner is online, works fine\r\n\r\n\r\n### Mix of request to join/join based on auto-approval\r\n\r\nThe rule is \"If auto-approval is on, show \"Join\", otherwise \"Request to join\"\r\n\r\n1) If the community has manual approval, show \"Request to join\", works ok\r\n2) If the community has auto approval, but the owner is offline/busy,  show \"Join\", but the user has to wait, which might not be expected\r\n3) If the community has auto approval, and the owner is online, we show \"Join\", works fine\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nI don't think we have any user research to backup any of the above to be honest, and that showing \"Join\", significantly increases engagement vs \"Request to join\".\r\n\r\nI'd go for either always showing \"Join\" or \"Request to join\" and keep it simple, that way we don't have to even pass the info that auto approval is on/off.\r\n\r\ncc @pedro-et @John-44 \r\n\r\n",
